**Describe your issue**

When I create a new `@utility` it does not apply styling if the utility contains a number. For instance:

```css
/* This won't work */
@utility h1 {
  @apply text-4xl font-bold;
}

/* But this will */
@utility hz {
  @apply text-4xl font-bold;
}
```

```jsx
export default function Home() {
  return (
    <div>
      <h1 className="h1">I don't work (class: h1)</h1>
      <h1 className="hz">I do work (class: hz)</h1>
    </div>
  );
}
```

When I use `@utility h-1` I do see some of my changes, but the actual `<h1>` element has some peculiar line-height settings.

This PR ensures that when we inject `layer(‚Ä¶)` into an `@import` that it always gets inserted as the first param. The `layer(‚Ä¶)` has to come first by spec.

Input:
```css
@import "./foo" supports(--foo);
```

Before:
```css
@import "./foo" supports(--foo) layer(utilities);
```

After:
```css
@import "./foo" layer(utilities) supports(--foo);
```

